The Ryder Cup is a biennial golf competition between teams from Europe and the United States. The competition is named after Samuel Ryder, a British businessman and amateur golfer.
The Ryder Cup is played over three days, with 12 players competing in four-ball and foursomes matches on the first two days, and 12 players competing in singles matches on the final day.
The Ryder Cup is played every two years, with the European team defending the cup in the odd-numbered years and the United States defending the cup in the even-numbered years.
The Ryder Cup is played at a different venue each time. The European team has won the cup 24 times, while the United States has won the cup 14 times.
The Ryder Cup is one of the most prestigious golf competitions in the world. It is also one of the most watched sporting events in the world.
